DateReviewed: 2026-01-08
Description: Our article today focuses on top 5 trends which will shape Kubernetes in 2026, at least according to the author. We start with a bit of author background, where he mentions he's been part of the Collabnix community for a while, before diving into predictions. First up is that AI workloads will become first class citizens - basically that AI are going to be given a prominent position in what can be run on a cluster. They point out announcements including the CNCF backing an AI measure as examples of this. Second up is WebAssembly emerging for Edge and Serverless workloads. WASM is lighter and more secure, so it's easy to see why it gets the nod. Next up is Platform engineering and GitOps becoming standard practice - this puts more automation and relaxes what Devs have to manage or know. Next up is Security first emphasis with hardened containers, using eBPF and zero trust -- all of which promote a more secure stance. Finally, they pose that multi-cluster mgmt and Edge computing will converge. The idea is to have one governance approach to multiple execution envs. An overall interesting take.
