DateReviewed: 2026-01-09
Description: Today's article are going to talk about open platforms and how they are going to boost the adoption of Kubernetes. We start with the usual background, and then hop into things. They talk about typical ways to use K8s - DIY, proprietary and the public cloud. While they have pros and cons the authors here advocate for a more open platform. We talk about each in turn - first, proprietary, where the starting barrier is low but often that comes at the expense of compatibility and customizations. What you value for innovation your vendor might not, and that can be a drag on your flexibility. We then look at DIY, where you have lots of control but also lots of responsibilities. There is also an infered technical ability for such a team. Finally, they looked at public cloud -- which is good, but can be costly. They contrast this with the open platform approach, which has the upsides of DIY but with the ease of use a cloud or proprietary system might have. They use Nutanix as an example of this - which does use some proprietary pieces out of the box, but can swap those with just open source ones.
